T1  - Do leveraged ETFs really amplify late-day returns and volatility?
AU  - Ivanov, Ivan T.
AU  - Lenkey, Stephen L.
JO  - Journal of Financial Markets
VL  - 41
SP  - 36
EP  - 56
PY  - 2018
DA  - 2018/11/01/
SN  - 1386-4181
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/j.finmar.2018.09.001
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1386418117302604
KW  - Leveraged ETFs
KW  - Capital flows
KW  - Late-day returns
KW  - Volatility
AB  - The design of leveraged and inverse exchange-traded funds (ETFs) has raised concerns that they may exacerbate volatility in financial markets by mechanically rebalancing their portfolios in the same direction as contemporaneous returns. We show theoretically, however, that capital flows can lower ETF rebalancing demand and completely eliminate it in the limit. Using a sample of U.S. equity-based ETFs from 2006 to 2014, we find that capital flows substantially reduce ETF rebalancing demand, even during periods of severe market stress. After accounting for capital flows and standard risk factors, we find that the impact of ETF rebalancing on late-day returns and volatility is economically insignificant.
